Director Control Artifact

Source-of-truth decision:
- This file is the active Director control artifact for the Machine Design Tree + Parameterized GameMaster Actions program.
- The initiating prompt also named local_docs/plans/authoritative_plan.md. That file is a pointer only to avoid a stale blank plan; do not maintain two full copies.
- Orchestrator and QA threads must use this file and the slice packet they receive, not the attachment or local_docs pointer.

Director State
- Current slice: Plan complete. Slice 14 final expert review is accepted with release-gate verdict GO WITH CAVEATS.
- Accepted decisions:
  - Bare-core legality direction is accepted for implementation unless a later human decision reverses it.
  - tools/goals/Authoritative Plan.doc is the authoritative plan/control file.
  - Slice 1 is accepted. Parameterized action contract/resolver/lock support is implemented; no machine placement behavior was added in Slice 1.
  - publicMessage remains part of GameMaster request hashing as inherited behavior for now. This is a logged API risk, not a Slice 1 blocker; revisit before final API review.
  - Slice 2 is accepted after follow-up. Active new-session loadout state now uses machine:v1 authority with core, while legacyDraft/currentDesign projection paths remain compatibility-only.
  - Slice 3 is accepted after follow-up. MachineDesign legacy projections are compatibility/replay/private-state only; machine:v1 combat is temporarily brake/hold-only with neutral resolver fallback until native capabilities/combat land; machine:v1 confirm uses MachineDesign tree validation.
  - Slice 3 temporary both-machine combat resolves as a no-damage draw after the first submitted hold pair to avoid inert 60-turn loops and rate-limit failure while native machine combat is absent.
  - Slice 4 is accepted after follow-up. Mount surfaces are schema/catalog/sim data, not renderer-owned; PartMountKind no longer includes fake "sphere" vocabulary; core/catalog expose core_shell, core_deck, deck_panel, and hull_shell surfaces.
  - Slice 4 ResolvedMountPose authority is position, surfaceNormal, orientation basis, and canonical params. It intentionally has no lossy transform/Euler output; legacy sector/cell mounts remain compatibility-only until Slice 5+ cleanup.
  - Slice 5 is accepted. Machine loadout placement now uses propose_mount_pose after choose_attach_target; parameters are validated through the action template/schema resolver; validateMountPoseInput/resolveMountPose run before gold spend or design mutation; choose_mount/choose_rotation/cellForMount remain legacy compatibility only.
  - Slice 5 residual risk: MachineDesign Transform3D.rotation still stores a legacy-compatible yaw/roll tuple derived from accepted pose params, not the full OrientationBasis. Slice 7/11 must not treat that tuple as full orientation authority; use or extend pose/orientation data before native capabilities/replay depend on local axes.
  - Slice 6 is accepted. Machine:v1 confirm now uses validateMachineTree plus validateMachinePhysicalLegality; bare core, decorative-only, weaponless, mobility-less, backward-weapon, and sideways-wheel machines are legal; disconnected, unknown catalog part, hard sibling AABB collision, and insufficient gold are rejected.
  - Slice 6 residual risk: hard collision validation is intentionally limited to current reliable data, using axis-aligned bounds for non-direct catalog-part overlaps. It is not oriented, mount-aware, parent/child-aware, or full physics collision.
  - Slice 7 is accepted. MachineCapabilities are derived from MachineDesign parts, catalog machine capability metadata, explicit transform.orientation basis, and runtime.orientationByInstanceId. deriveControls and BotBlueprint/BotDesignSnapshot projections are not machine capability authority.
  - Slice 7 residual risk: orientation basis validation is finite/shape-only and trusts upstream pose/runtime producers for unit/orthogonal basis correctness. Full orientation-basis corpus testing remains deferred.
  - Slice 8 is accepted. Machine:v1 combat action generation now uses MachineCapabilities from deriveMachineCapabilities instead of temporary hold-only GeneratedControls or projection-derived controls. Resolver physics/runtime mutation remains deferred to Slice 9.
  - Slice 8 residual risk: no wreckage entity exists before Slice 10, so LOS blocker proof is limited to current arena obstacles; machine weapon readiness in the AI combat brief still inherits current snapshot range semantics until native machine runtime reaches the resolver.
  - Slice 9 is accepted. Machine:v1 combat now resolves movement and weapon fire through native MachineDesign, MachineRuntimeState, and MachineCapabilities authority. Machine movement uses shared capability axes rather than moveBot, deriveControls, or fallback blueprint authority.
  - Slice 9 blocker fixes are accepted. Worker cumulative replay stores per-combat baseline machine designs to avoid double-applying prior submitted ticks after runtime persistence, while persisted runtime still feeds next-turn packet/action generation. Native machine weapon damage now writes flat healthByInstanceId through precise runtime sync without adding detach, wreckage, or breakage semantics.
  - Slice 9 residual risk: mixed legacy-vs-machine combat is minimally supported but not deeply characterized. No browser/replay visual QA was run because Slice 9 did not change renderer/Babylon behavior; replay proof remains mandatory in Slice 11.
  - Slice 10 is accepted after follow-up. Machine:v1 damage now applies through native MachineRuntimeState health, destroyed/detached capability suppression, child-subtree detach, and semantic part_detach wreckage events. Machine damage/detach/wreckage authority is native MachineDesign/MachineRuntimeState data, not legacy projections.
  - Slice 10 blocker fix is accepted. Machine weapon resolution now reads refreshed attacker.machine.capabilities at fire time, so a machine weapon destroyed earlier in the same tick cannot fire from a stale pre-damage capability snapshot.
  - Slice 10 residual risk: current weapon submissions still identify weaponA/weaponB slots rather than stable part instance ids, so live capability refresh can suppress a surviving second weapon if slot order shifts after same-tick damage. Detached descendants are runtime-health-zeroed immediately; Slice 11 may need richer visual metadata for detached-but-recognizable wreckage.
  - Slice 11 is accepted after follow-up. Machine replay renders MachineDesign parts directly with machine:v1 visual authority; the legacy foundation-shell path is quarantined behind a named legacy adapter; the machine proof fixture supplies both red and blue MachineDesigns; public replay machine payload normalization now validates nested machine shape before renderer use.
  - Slice 11 residual risk: replay machine payload validation is structural and finite-shape validation, not full semantic graph validation. Replay payloads still carry the stored machine design/runtime snapshot rather than a per-frame time-sliced runtime snapshot; this is accepted as non-blocking unless future replay requires frame-exact part runtime history.
  - Slice 12 is accepted. Agent contract, samples, brief, cockpit, and workbench guidance now tell agents to inspect legal-action parameterSchema, submit parameters only when the selected action asks for them, expect server/shop/budget rejection of invalid or stale submissions, and understand that bad, weaponless, or mobility-less machine designs can still be legal.
  - Slice 12 correction: the live propose_mount_pose schema uses yawDegrees and rollDegrees. The stale yawDeg/rollDeg examples in the packet/control artifact were corrected before Slice 13 was prepared.
  - Slice 13 is accepted. Legacy authority-looking symbols were removed or quarantined: validateMinimumViableLoadout is now validateLegacyMinimumViableLoadout, cellForMount/isConnectedGrid helpers have legacy names, retained selectedAttachCell/selectedMountSector/selectedRotation fields have legacy removal notes, deriveControls is marked legacy projection, and forged machine:v1 choose_mount/choose_rotation legacy-grid apply paths now reject with LEGACY_GRID_ACTION_REJECTED.
  - Slice 14 is accepted. Final expert panel reviewers passed architecture, Schema/API after blocker fixes, GameMaster/worker, sim, replay/Babylon, UI/agent, and cleanup lanes. Release gate verdict is GO WITH CAVEATS, not clean GO, because the worktree is heavily dirty/uncommitted by design and replay/browser proof was not rerun after final non-renderer schema/worker cleanup.
